(1144, 'Introduction to Communication Science', 'Since Antiquity, scholars have appreciated the importance of communication: as social beings, we cannot exist without communication. The course extends beyond the boundaries of communication science itself, exploring dimensions of history, sociology and psychology. Join our class, together with people all over the world.\n', '<p>Since Antiquity,\nscholars have appreciated the importance of communication: as social beings, we\ncannot exist without communication. We need to interact with people around us,\nto make sense of the world and to position ourselves in a wider social and\ncultural reality. In this course, we look at how and why communication evolved\nas a science and reflect on today’s dominant paradigms. The course also extends\nbeyond the boundaries of communication science itself, exploring dimensions of\nhistory, sociology and psychology. Join our class, together with people all\nover the world.</p>\n\nIntroduction to Communication Science explores some of the basic \ntheories, models and concepts from the fields of mass, interpersonal and\n intrapersonal communication. The course begins with a consideration of \nseveral basic models, subsequently progressing to the history of \ncommunication theory, linear effect-oriented theories, the reception \napproach and, finally, exploring theories on the production and \nreinforcement of culture through communication. <br>\n<br>\nUpon completion of this course, students should:<br>\n•	have knowledge of the history and development of communication science; <br>\n•	have knowledge of the dominant theoretical approaches within communication science; <br>\n•	have knowledge and understanding of the most important models and concepts in this field. <br><br>', 'https://www.coursera.org/course/commscience', 'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aMpV5A7bpog', '2014-01-15', 8, 'https://coursera-course-photos.s3.amazonaws.com/74/b4c3a75149b177d8cfbcfba7de3b14/Laswell2.png', 'Business & Management', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'yes', ' University of Amsterdam', '2014-05-18 22:43:07'),
(1145, 'Introduction to Communication Science', 'Since Antiquity, scholars have appreciated the importance of communication: as social beings, we cannot exist without communication. The course extends beyond the boundaries of communication science itself, exploring dimensions of history, sociology and psychology. Join our class, together with people all over the world.\n', '<p>Since Antiquity,\nscholars have appreciated the importance of communication: as social beings, we\ncannot exist without communication. We need to interact with people around us,\nto make sense of the world and to position ourselves in a wider social and\ncultural reality. In this course, we look at how and why communication evolved\nas a science and reflect on today’s dominant paradigms. The course also extends\nbeyond the boundaries of communication science itself, exploring dimensions of\nhistory, sociology and psychology. Join our class, together with people all\nover the world.</p>\n\nIntroduction to Communication Science explores some of the basic \ntheories, models and concepts from the fields of mass, interpersonal and\n intrapersonal communication. The course begins with a consideration of \nseveral basic models, subsequently progressing to the history of \ncommunication theory, linear effect-oriented theories, the reception \napproach and, finally, exploring theories on the production and \nreinforcement of culture through communication. <br>\n<br>\nUpon completion of this course, students should:<br>\n•	have knowledge of the history and development of communication science; <br>\n•	have knowledge of the dominant theoretical approaches within communication science; <br>\n•	have knowledge and understanding of the most important models and concepts in this field. <br><br>', 'https://www.coursera.org/course/commscience', 'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aMpV5A7bpog', '2014-07-02', 7, 'https://coursera-course-photos.s3.amazonaws.com/74/b4c3a75149b177d8cfbcfba7de3b14/Laswell2.png', 'Business & Management', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'yes', ' University of Amsterdam', '2014-05-18 22:43:07'),
(1146, 'Preparing for the AP* Calculus AB and BC Exams', 'This six week course will help students prepare for the AP* Calculus AB Exam.\n\n* AP Calculus is a registered trademark of the College Board, which was not involved in the production of, and does not endorse, this product.', 'This course reviews the topics for the AP Calculus AB Exam. Each week of the six week review will include review videos for an important block of material, complete with videos of worked example problems and exam tips. There will also be an extensive online quiz given each week, with multiple problem versions that students can use to practice, along with an practice tests to help students prepare for the AP* Calculus AB Exam.<br><br>* AP Calculus is a registered trademark of the College Board, which was not involved in the production of, and does not endorse, this product.', 'https://www.coursera.org/course/apcalc', 'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iCaBB6RxJSY', '2014-03-17', 8, 'https://coursera-course-photos.s3.amazonaws.com/5d/bca190749111e3bea989765a5f4524/calc_mooc_image.png', 'Mathematics', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'yes', ' University of Houston System', '2014-05-18 22:43:08'),
(1147, 'Statistical Mechanics: Algorithms and Computations', 'In this course you will learn a whole lot of modern physics (classical and quantum) from basic computer programs that you will download, generalize, or write from scratch, discuss, and then hand in. Join in if you are curious (but not necessarily knowledgeable) about algorithms, and about the deep insights into science that you can obtain by the algorithmic approach.', '<div>This\n course discusses the computational approach in modern physics in a \nclear yet accessible way. Individual modules contain in-depth \ndiscussions of algorithms ranging from basic enumeration methods to cutting-edge Markov-chain techniques. Emphasis will be put on \napplications in classical and quantum physics. The focus\n will be on subjects such as Monte Carlo sampling, molecular \ndynamics, transition phases in hard-sphere liquids, simulated annealing \nfor solving geometrical constraints, perfect sampling of classical spin \nmodels, to aspects of quantum Monte Carlo algorithms, Bose-Einstein \ncondensation, and many-body physics with fermions. <span>The emphasis is on orientation. Discussion of implementation details will be kept to a minimum.</span></div>\n<p>\nThe course is entirely\nself-contained. It heavily relies on concise algorithms  (each\nwith between 10 and  50 lines of Python code). Modules lead from\nelementary discussions to the rich and difficult problems in\ncontemporary physics, and are of interest to a wide range of students\nin the natural sciences.</p><br>', 'https://www.coursera.org/course/smac', 'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j-Y4ogZNr_I', '2014-02-03', 10, 'https://coursera-course-photos.s3.amazonaws.com/13/8c315232b22ca1039266092dfb11dc/mooc_statistical_mechanics_2609.png', 'Computer Science: Theory', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'yes', ' École normale supérieure', '2014-05-18 22:43:08'),
(1148, 'Making Better Group Decisions: Voting, Judgement Aggregation and Fair Division', 'Learn about different voting methods and fair division algorithms, and explore the problems that arise when a group of people need to make a decision.  ', '<div>\n			<div>\n				<div>\n					<p>Much of our daily life is spent taking part in various types of what we might call “political”\nprocedures. Examples range from voting in a national election to deliberating with others\nin small committees. Many interesting philosophical and mathematical issues arise when\nwe carefully examine our group decision-making processes.&nbsp;</p><p>There are two types of group\ndecision making problems that we will discuss in this course. A <i>voting problem</i>: Suppose\nthat a group of friends are deciding where to go for dinner. If everyone agrees on which\nrestaurant is best, then it is obvious where to go. But, how should the friends decide where\nto go if they have different opinions about which restaurant is best? Can we always find a\nchoice that is “fair” taking into account everyone’s opinions or must we choose one person\nfrom the group to act as a “dictator”? A <i>fair division problem</i>: Suppose that there is a cake and\na group of hungry children. Naturally, you want to cut the cake and distribute the pieces\nto the children as fairly as possible. If the cake is homogeneous (e.g., a chocolate cake with\nvanilla icing evenly distributed), then it is easy to find a fair division: give each child a piece\nthat is the same size. But, how do we find a “fair” division of the cake if it is heterogeneous\n(e.g., icing that is 1/3 chocolate, 1/3 vanilla and 1/3 strawberry) and the children each want\ndifferent parts of the cake?&nbsp;</p>\n				</div>\n			</div>\n		</div>', 'https://www.coursera.org/course/votingfairdiv', 'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KOEVQ_2fmIQ', '2014-01-27', 7, 'https://coursera-course-photos.s3.amazonaws.com/c9/68becd69bfac902edd2ea292619756/coursera_decisions.png', 'Economics & Finance', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'yes', ' University of Maryland, College Park', '2014-05-18 22:43:09'),
(1149, 'Making Better Group Decisions: Voting, Judgement Aggregation and Fair Division', 'Learn about different voting methods and fair division algorithms, and explore the problems that arise when a group of people need to make a decision.  ', '<div>\n			<div>\n				<div>\n					<p>Much of our daily life is spent taking part in various types of what we might call “political”\nprocedures. Examples range from voting in a national election to deliberating with others\nin small committees. Many interesting philosophical and mathematical issues arise when\nwe carefully examine our group decision-making processes.&nbsp;</p><p>There are two types of group\ndecision making problems that we will discuss in this course. A <i>voting problem</i>: Suppose\nthat a group of friends are deciding where to go for dinner. If everyone agrees on which\nrestaurant is best, then it is obvious where to go. But, how should the friends decide where\nto go if they have different opinions about which restaurant is best? Can we always find a\nchoice that is “fair” taking into account everyone’s opinions or must we choose one person\nfrom the group to act as a “dictator”? A <i>fair division problem</i>: Suppose that there is a cake and\na group of hungry children. Naturally, you want to cut the cake and distribute the pieces\nto the children as fairly as possible. If the cake is homogeneous (e.g., a chocolate cake with\nvanilla icing evenly distributed), then it is easy to find a fair division: give each child a piece\nthat is the same size. But, how do we find a “fair” division of the cake if it is heterogeneous\n(e.g., icing that is 1/3 chocolate, 1/3 vanilla and 1/3 strawberry) and the children each want\ndifferent parts of the cake?&nbsp;</p>\n				</div>\n			</div>\n		</div>', 'https://www.coursera.org/course/votingfairdiv', 'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KOEVQ_2fmIQ', '3000-00-00', 7, 'https://coursera-course-photos.s3.amazonaws.com/c9/68becd69bfac902edd2ea292619756/coursera_decisions.png',